'''Tanao Shrine''' ({{nihongo|棚尾神社|1=Tanao Gokoku Shrine|Tanao Jinja}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Yayoi Town, Hekinan|ja|弥生町 (碧南市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yayoi Town, Hekinan|1=Yayoi-machi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q66041243}}, {{ill|Hekinan|en|Hekinan|WD=Q495802|lt=Hekinan|1=Hekinan}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|en|Aichi Prefecture|WD=Q80434|lt=Aichi Prefecture|1=Aichi Prefecture}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|Gokoku shrines|en|Gokoku shrines|WD=Q1534477|lt=Gokoku shrine|1=Gokoku Shrines}}, dedicated to the spirits of war heroes.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} The shrine is an external precinct of the nearby {{ill|Yahashira Shrine (Hekinan)|ja|八柱神社 (碧南市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yahashira Shrine (Hekinan)|qq=}}.

Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|WD=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|WD=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

== History ==
Tanao Shrine was originally established as Tanao Shōkonsha (招魂社). In 1931, it was renamed Tanao Chūkonsha (忠魂社), and in 1950, it received its current name, Tanao Shrine.<ref name="aichi_e_1">『愛知県下英霊社忠魂碑等調査報告書（第一輯）』愛知県護国神社　ISBN 4-87161-056-X C3014</ref> The shrine enshrines the spirits of 195 war heroes from the Tanao area.<ref name="aichi_e_1"/>

<gallery widths="170px">
Tanao-jinja-monument.jpg|Memorial Monument
</gallery>

